<paragraph blockId="21.[699,1228,662,1741]" lastBlockId="22.[124,653,1113,1253]" lastPageId="22" lastPageNumber="23" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
The follicular tissue was difficult to remove from the oocytes of this species and all other melectines examined in this study. For this reason, we were unable to examine the micropylar region of 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Melecta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="albifrons" subSpecies="albovaria">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Melecta albifrons albovaria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The change in chorionic microstructure at the extreme posterior end may somehow relate to the mechanism of attachment of the egg to the cell closure.
</paragraph>
